            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Svetlana Orlova\u2019s story begins not in the fog of San Francisco, but in the industrial grit of Yekaterinburg, Russia. Born during the twilight of the Soviet era, her upbringing was defined by pragmatism and resilience. Her father worked in a factory, her mother taught math, and they instilled in Svetlana a profound sense of duty and the value of quiet, consistent work.\n\nThe chaos of the 1990s presented a turning point. With a young son, Dmitri, and a crumbling economy, the future in Russia felt uncertain. In 1999, sponsored by a distant cousin, she made the momentous decision to immigrate, landing in a city that felt like another planet: San Francisco. She found a small, familiar world in the Outer Richmond, a neighborhood filled with the sounds and smells of her homeland\u2014Russian bakeries, Orthodox churches, and conversations in her native tongue.\n\nWith a Russian high school diploma that held little weight, her career began with a series of strenuous, low-wage jobs. She cleaned houses and worked in the kitchens of Russian delis, pouring every spare dollar into Dmitri\u2019s future. It was through a community connection that she found her calling as a home health aide. She discovered a deep well of patience and empathy, a quiet strength that calmed her elderly clients. Caring for others became more than a job; it was an extension of the duty she was raised to value.\n\nSvetlana\u2019s daily life is a testament to routine. She wakes before dawn in her small, rent-controlled apartment, catching the 38 Geary MUNI bus for the 4.5-mile commute to her clients in more affluent neighborhoods. Her social circle is small but deep, consisting of a few friends from her church and her son, Dmitri, now a successful graphic designer, who remains the quiet pillar of her life.\n\nAt 50, Svetlana doesn\u2019t dream of wealth. Her aspirations are etched with pragmatism: to see her son happy, to maintain her health, and to one day sit on a bench at Land's End, watching the ships pass without the low hum of financial anxiety. San Francisco is not a city she conquered, but one she has learned to coexist with, finding her own pockets of peace and purpose within its demanding embrace."
